snippet.textDisplay:
Nouka Baich (Bengali: নৌকা বাইচ, lit. Boat Race, also spelt Nowka Bais) is a traditional dragon boat-style paddling sport of Bangladesh. The Bangladesh Rowing Federation, established in 1974, is the authority of all rowing activities in Bangladesh and has organised over 40 National Rowing Championships. The races are held during the wet and autumn seasons of the Bengali calendar which corresponds from June to October in the Gregorian calendar. The "Nowka Bais" which takes place annually in Birmingham is a leading cultural event in the West Midlands, United Kingdom attracting not only the Bangladeshi diaspora but a variety of cultures.
Boats used for Nouka Baich are long with each team can consist from 7 to up to 100 members known as majhis. Boats with motor engines are not allowed. Boats are usually named with attractive and boastful names displaying quality and speed. During inter-riverine competitions, teams are named after their respective 'home rivers'. It is also a social event, and it is common for the competitors to sing Sari gan folk songs as they compete during the race. A popular song is "Ronger Nao Ronger Boitha, Ronge Ronge Bao" (Cheerfully tune the colourful oars of the colourful boat)
"Deora" (Brother in law) is a remarkable song that showcase of  the beauty of Bangladeshi folk songs. 
The commination and new creation is awesome. Appreciate it.
Few years back in 2019 this song was sang in the Jamuna River, Sirajganj.  Boat roaring/ race programme.  I still remember those days.🥰

 #cokestudiobangla, last two song is the best in this #season2. Keep it up 👍 we want to see more of masterpiece from here and represent our Bengali culture to the world.❤❤❤
